    <stitle>POWER STEERING GEAR: TRW/ROSS-TAS 40, 55, 65 AND 85 - INPUT SHAFT SEAL - INSTALL</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="install" graphiccount="5">
        <title>INSTALL</title>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Put clean grease (NLGI LB or GC-LB) on the inside diameter of the new input shaft seal and
                place it over the input shaft. With the small diameter of the seal driver against the seal, tap the tool
                until the tool shoulder is square against the valve housing (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500314">Figure 14</hotlnk>). Remove any seal material that may have sheared off in the
                seal bore or retaining ring groove.
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500314" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500314" filename="../figg05/G0500314.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 14. Input Shaft Seal Installation</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <important>
                    <para>Do not use a socket to install this seal because you will not be able to control seal
                        installation depth, possibly causing a leak.
                    </para>
                </important>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Insert new retaining ring into the groove (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500315">Figure 15</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500315" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500315" filename="../figg05/G0500315.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 15. Input Shaft Seal Installation</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Pack the end of the valve housing bore around the input shaft with clean, high temperature
                industrial grease. Apply more of the grease to a new dirt and water seal and install it over the input
                shaft. Seat it in the groove behind the serrations and against the valve housing (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500316">Figure 16</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500316" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500316" filename="../figg05/G0500316.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 16. Input Shaft Seal Installation</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Reconnect the steering column to the input shaft and tighten the pinch bolt nut until
                unthreaded portion above plastic collar shears off (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500317">Figure 17</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500317" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500317" filename="../figg05/G0500317.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 17. Input Shaft Seal Installation</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <important>
                    <para>Always use a new pinch bolt and nut whenever re-installing the steering column to the steering
                        gear.
                    </para>
                </important>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Reconnect the return line to the steering gear return port (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500318">Figure 18</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0500318" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500318" filename="../figg05/G0500318.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 18. Input Shaft Seal Installation</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Bleed system. Refer to ,
                <hotlnk document="s05003y_HL0500303.xml" xrefid="hl0500303">FILLING AND AIR BLEEDING THE SYSTEM</hotlnk>
                .
            </para>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
